const a = [
  {"id":1380,"text":"During translation, the initiation codon of mRNA attaches to the ribosome at which site?","explanation":null,"reference":"Sanvictores T, Farci F. Biochemistry, primary protein structure. In: StatPearls. StatPearls Publishing; 2022. Accessed April 9, 2022. http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK564343/","responses":[{"text":"A site of 50S subunit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"E site of 50S subunit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"P site of 30S subunit","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"E site of 30S subunit","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"A site of 30S subunit","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9570,"text":"From which of the following does the external urethral meatus develop?","explanation":"The **external urethral meatus** develops from the **surface ectoderm** as ectodermal cells from the tip of the glans penetrate inward during the 4th month of uterine life. This process results in the formation of a short epithelial cord. Subsequent canalization of this cord gives rise to the urethral, thus forming the external urethral meatus.\r\n\r\n***\r\n\r\nThe scrotal swellings develop into the scrotum, not the external urethral meatus.\r\n\r\nThe phallus is the embryonic structure that develops into the penis in males and the clitoris in females. While it plays a role in the overall development of the external genitalia, it does not specifically contribute to the formation of the external urethral meatus.\r\n\r\nAnal folds contribute to the development of the anus, not the urethra.\r\n\r\nUrethral folds play a crucial role in the formation of the penile urethra. However, the lumen of this structure is terminated before it reaches the distal end of the phallus. The remaining part of the urethra, which resides in the glans penis, arises from the surface ectoderm.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 276, 277.","responses":[{"text":"Anal folds","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Scrotal swellings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Surface ectoderm","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Phallus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urethral folds","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":9679,"text":"A woman presents to the clinic with the complaint of cessation of the menstrual cycle for the last 3 months. Previously she had regular menstruation occurring every 30th day and continued for 4 days. On what day of the cycle this woman is most likely to ovulate?","explanation":"The woman in this scenario is most likely to ovulate around the **16th day** of her menstrual cycle. Ovulation typically occurs approximately 14 days before the onset of the next menstrual period. Since her regular **menstrual cycle** was **30 days**, Since her cycle length is 30 days, ovulation would be expected around the 16th day (30 - 14 = 16).\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\nThe 14th day is a common misconception as it represents an average timing for ovulation in a textbook 28-day cycle. However, in this case, with a 30-day cycle, ovulation is more likely to occur around the 16th day.\r\n\r\nThe 28th day corresponds to the end of the menstrual cycle, and ovulation generally occurs before this phase.\r\n\r\nThe 30th day marks the expected onset of the next menstrual period, making it less likely for ovulation to occur on this day.\r\n\r\nThe 7th day is early in the menstrual cycle, and ovulation typically takes place later, around the midpoint, as seen in a regular 30-day cycle.","reference":null,"responses":[{"text":"14th day","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"7th day","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"30th day","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"16th day","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"28th day","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":11520,"text":"Which enzyme is responsible for releasing DNA supercoils?","explanation":"The enzyme responsible for releasing DNA supercoils is **topoisomerase**. Topoisomerases are essential enzymes that manage the topological states of DNA. They function by transiently cutting one or both strands of the DNA helix, allowing for the relaxation of supercoils that form during processes like DNA replication and transcription, and then resealing the breaks. This activity is crucial for the proper functioning of DNA replication and transcription, as supercoiled DNA can hinder the progress of DNA and RNA polymerases. \r\n\r\nDNA ligase is involved in joining DNA strands together, particularly during DNA replication and repair. RNA polymerase is responsible for synthesizing RNA from a DNA template. Helicase unwinds the double-stranded DNA helix into single strands, facilitating replication or transcription. Single-strand DNA is not an enzyme but a product of DNA unwinding.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2017: 417.","responses":[{"text":"DNA ligase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"RNA polymerase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Single strand DNA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Helicase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Topoisomerase","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":12921,"text":"Which type of epithelial transition is seen between the vagina and cervix?","explanation":"The epithelial lining of the **vagina** is primarily composed of **stratified squamous** (nonkeratinized) epithelium. This type of epithelium is well-suited to withstand friction and stretching, protecting the vaginal canal.\r\n\r\nThe **cervix** is characterized by a transformation from stratified squamous epithelium in the vagina to **simple columnar epithelium** in the endocervical canal. This transitional region is known as the **transformation zone**.\r\n\r\nThe reason for this transition is related to the different functions of the vagina and cervix. The stratified squamous epithelium in the vagina provides protection, while the simple columnar epithelium in the cervix is involved in mucous secretion and is more conducive to the transport of sperm.","reference":"Laiq Hussain Siddiqui. Medical Histology Text And Atlas. 6th ed. Paramount; 2019: 239.","responses":[{"text":"Simple squamous to stratified columnar epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple squamous to simple columnar epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous to simple columnar epithelium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Stratified squamous to stratified columnar epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Simple columnar to simple squamous epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21877,"text":"Which of the following structures surrounds part of the urethra?","explanation":"The **prostate gland** is a male reproductive organ located just below the bladder and surrounds the urethra as it exits the bladder and enters the penis. It is responsible for producing prostatic fluid, which is a major component of semen. The prostatic fluid contains enzymes and nutrients that help support sperm function and viability.\r\n\r\nThe position of the prostate gland around the urethra means that it plays a crucial role in the process of ejaculation. During ejaculation, the prostate contracts and releases its prostatic fluid into the urethra. This fluid then mixes with sperm from the testes and seminal vesicles to form semen, which is ejaculated from the penis during sexual intercourse.\r\n\r\nAny issues with the prostate, such as enlargement or inflammation, can potentially affect the flow of urine through the urethra and may lead to symptoms like difficulty urinating, frequent urination, or urinary retention. Prostate-related conditions, such as benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) or prostate cancer, are common in older men and often require medical attention.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 461.","responses":[{"text":"Vas deferens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostate","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Bulbourethral gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Seminal vesicles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epididymis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21878,"text":"Which part of the levator ani muscle plays a major role in maintaining fecal continence?","explanation":"The levator ani muscle is a critical part of the pelvic floor and is responsible for supporting various pelvic organs, including the rectum. Within the levator ani muscle, the **puborectalis** muscle forms a sling-like structure that wraps around the rectum. This muscular sling creates a natural kink or angle where the rectum meets the anus, known as the anorectal angle. The puborectalis muscle actively contracts and relaxes to help control the passage of feces through the rectum and into the anal canal.\r\n\r\nDuring rest, the puborectalis muscle maintains constriction, preventing involuntary passage of stool. When it relaxes during defecation, it allows for the passage of feces.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 448.","responses":[{"text":"Puboannalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pubococcygeus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Iliococcygeus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Puborectalis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Puboperinealis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21880,"text":"The placenta is composed of two parts: 5/6th fetal and 1/6th maternal. The maternal placenta is formed by which of the following?","explanation":"During pregnancy, the developing placenta interfaces with the maternal uterine lining. This interaction leads to the formation of several specialized layers. The **decidua basalis** is one of these layers, and it is the maternal part of the placenta. The decidua basalis is the area of the uterine endometrium (the lining of the uterus) where the placenta attaches and establishes a connection with the fetal chorion frondosum, which is the specialized fetal tissue that contributes to the placental formation.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 113.","responses":[{"text":"Decidua parietalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decidua basalis and chorion frondosum","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chorion laeve","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decidua basalis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decidua capsularis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21881,"text":"Which of the following is not included in the boundaries of perineum?","explanation":"The perineum is the anatomical region below the pelvic diaphragm, between the upper thighs. Its boundaries are more specifically defined as:\r\n\r\nAnteriorly, by the inferior border of the pubic symphysis.\r\nPosteriorly, by the tip of the coccyx.\r\nLaterally, by the ischial tuberosities and further defined by the ischiopubic rami anteriorly and by the sacrotuberous ligaments posteriorly.\r\n\r\nAn **imaginary line joining two ischial tuberosities** is not a recognized boundary of the perineum. Instead, the ischial tuberosities themselves serve as lateral points of reference for the perineal","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 496.","responses":[{"text":"Pubic symphysis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischiopubic rami","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Imaginary line joining two ischial tuberosities","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Coccyx","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischial tuberosity","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21882,"text":"Which of the following glands are located in the deep perineal pouch of males?","explanation":"The deep perineal pouch, also known as the deep perineal space, is a compartment within the male perineum. It is bounded by several structures, including the perineal membrane superiorly and the pelvic diaphragm inferiorly. This pouch contains various structures, including the **bulbourethral glands**.\r\n\r\nThe bulbourethral glands, also known as Cowper's glands, are a pair of small exocrine glands located on either side of the membranous urethra, which passes through the deep perineal pouch. These glands secrete a clear, viscous fluid into the urethra during sexual arousal. This fluid helps to lubricate the urethra and neutralize any residual acidic urine, creating a more favorable environment for sperm as they pass through the urethra.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 461.","responses":[{"text":"Bulbourethral glands","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostatic glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Seminal vesicles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Modified sweat glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urethral glands","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21883,"text":"Which of the following does not form the placental barrier?","explanation":"The placental barrier is a specialized structure that separates maternal and fetal blood circulation within the placenta, allowing for the exchange of nutrients, gases, and waste products while preventing direct mixing of maternal and fetal blood. This barrier is primarily formed by two layers of trophoblastic cells: the **syncytiotrophoblast** and the **cytotrophoblast.**\r\n\r\nSyncytiotrophoblast is the outermost layer of trophoblastic cells and plays a crucial role in the exchange of substances between maternal and fetal blood. It is a multinucleated, syncytial layer that directly contacts the maternal blood within the intervillous spaces of the placenta.\r\n\r\nThe cytotrophoblast is the inner layer of trophoblastic cells and provides support to the syncytiotrophoblast. It contributes to the formation of placental villi and is involved in early placental development.\r\n\r\nIn addition to these trophoblastic layers, the placental barrier also includes **capillary endothelium,** which lines the fetal capillaries within the villi, and connective tissue that provides structural support.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 118.","responses":[{"text":"Capillary endothelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Syncytiotrophoblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cytotrophoblast","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Connective tissue","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Amniotic membrane","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21884,"text":"Which of the following sites in the male reproductive system is associated with storage and maturation of sperms?","explanation":"The **epididymis** is a tightly coiled tubular structure located on the posterior surface of each testis. It serves as a conduit for sperm transport from the testis to the vas deferens, which eventually leads to the urethra. More importantly, the epididymis provides a conducive microenvironment for sperm maturation and storage.\r\n\r\nSperm, produced in the seminiferous tubules of the testis, are initially immature and incapable of fertilization. As sperm pass through the epididymis, they undergo a maturation process that includes acquiring the ability to swim (motility) and the capability to fertilize an egg. The epididymis also serves as a storage site for mature sperm until they are ejaculated during sexual intercourse.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 464.","responses":[{"text":"Epididymis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Seminal vesicles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vas deferens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostate gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Seminiferous tubules","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21885,"text":"Which of the following correctly identifies the normal description of the uterus?","explanation":"**Anteverted** means that the uterus is tilted forward, with its fundus pointing toward the anterior abdominal wall.\r\n\r\n**Anteflexed** means that the body of the uterus is flexed forward at the level of the cervix, creating a slight bend at this point.\r\n\r\nThis positioning is considered the typical and normal orientation of the uterus within the female pelvis. It allows the uterus to occupy a position that is conducive to its reproductive functions, including pregnancy.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 473.","responses":[{"text":"Retroflexed and anteverted","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anteflexed and retroverted","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anteflexed and anteverted","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anteverted and retroextended","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Retroflexed and retroverted","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21886,"text":"Which of the following is true regarding the blood supply of the prostate gland?","explanation":"The prostate gland receives its blood supply primarily from the **inferior vesical artery**, which is a branch of the **internal iliac artery**. This artery is responsible for delivering oxygenated blood to the prostate, ensuring its proper function. The **middle rectal artery**, another branch of the internal iliac artery, also contributes to the blood supply of the prostate.","reference":"Moore KL, Agur AMR, Dalley AF. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 353, 607.","responses":[{"text":"Branch of external iliac artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Middle rectal artery","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior vesical artery","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Artery of vas deferens","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Superior rectal artery","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21887,"text":"The urogenital triangle is not bounded by which of the following?","explanation":"The **coccyx** is not considered part of the urogenital triangle. The urogenital triangle is an anatomical region in the perineum, which lies between the pubic symphysis at the front and the coccyx at the back of the pelvis. It is primarily involved in housing and supporting the external genitalia, as well as structures related to urination and defecation. \r\n\r\nThe **pubic symphysis** serves as the anterior boundary of the urogenital triangle and is formed by the fusion of the two pubic bones. On the other hand, the **ischial tuberosities** are the bony prominences found on each side of the pelvis, which contribute to the lateral boundaries of the urogenital triangle. Additionally, the **ischial rami** connect the ischial tuberosities to the pubic symphysis, further defining the boundaries of this anatomical region.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 500.","responses":[{"text":"Ischial tuberosity","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ischial rami","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coccyx","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pubic rami","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pubic symphysis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21932,"text":"Which of the following landmarks is not a part of linea terminalis?","explanation":"The landmark that is not a part of the linea terminalis is the **Medial border of ilium**. The linea terminalis, an important anatomical feature in the pelvis, is a ridge that outlines the pelvic inlet, separating the greater (false) pelvis from the lesser (true) pelvis. It is comprised of the following structures:\r\n\r\nThe sacral promontory, which is the anterior edge of the first sacral vertebra.\r\nThe arcuate line, a curved line on the ilium located just below the iliac fossa.\r\nThe pectineal line of the pubis, a ridge on the superior pubic ramus.\r\nThe pubic crest, which is part of the pubic bone.","reference":"(1) Lesser pelvis - an overview | sciencedirect topics. Accessed January 3, 2024. https://www.sciencedirect.com/topics/immunology-and-microbiology/lesser-pelvis\r\n\r\n(2) Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 436.","responses":[{"text":"Medial border of ilium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Pectineal line of pubis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sacral promontory","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Arcuate line","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Pubic crest","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21933,"text":"What is the primary function of Leydig cells in the testes?","explanation":"The primary function of **Leydig cells** in the testes is **testosterone production**. These specialized cells are located in the interstitial spaces of the testicular tissue and play a crucial role in the endocrine function of the testes.\r\n\r\nLeydig cells are responsible for synthesizing and secreting testosterone, which is a male sex hormone and an androgen. Testosterone is essential for various physiological processes in males, including the development of secondary sexual characteristics, such as facial and body hair growth, deepening of the voice, and muscle mass development. It also plays a vital role in maintaining libido (sex drive) and overall reproductive function.\r\n\r\nSustentacular cells (Sertoli cells) are involved in supporting and nourishing developing sperm cells and aiding in spermatogenesis.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1013.","responses":[{"text":"Sustentacular cell production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Growth hormone secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Sperm production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Testosterone production","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hormonal regulation","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21934,"text":"Which of the following structures forms labia minora of the female external genitalia?","explanation":"During the development of the external genitalia in females, the embryonic structures undergo differentiation and fusion to form the labia minora. The **urethral fold** gives rise to this important part of the female external genitalia. The genital tubercle, on the other hand, develops into the clitoris, while the genital swelling forms the labia majora.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 278.","responses":[{"text":"Phallus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anal fold","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Urethral fold","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Genital swelling","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Genital tubercle","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21937,"text":"Which cells surround and nurture developing oocytes within the ovary?","explanation":"**Granulosa cells** are essential components of the ovarian follicles and are intimately involved in the process of oogenesis (egg development) and folliculogenesis (development of ovarian follicles). These cells form multiple layers around the developing oocyte, providing crucial support and nourishment.\r\n\r\nGranulosa cells play a vital role in follicular development by producing hormones such as **estrogens** and **inhibin**, which regulate the maturation of the oocyte and the menstrual cycle. They are also responsible for secreting the follicular fluid, which contains nutrients and growth factors that support the oocyte's growth and development.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1027.","responses":[{"text":"Epithelial cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Theca externa cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Granulosa cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Luteal cells","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21938,"text":"Which of the following properties of the prostatic capsule differentiates it from other glandular capsules?","explanation":"**Smooth muscle fibers** are a unique characteristic of the prostatic capsule, setting it apart from other glandular capsules. These smooth muscle fibers are responsible for contracting and exerting pressure on the gland, which aids in the expulsion of prostatic secretions during ejaculation.","reference":"Mescher AL, Junqueira LCU. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 16th ed. McGraw-Hill; 2021: 453.","responses":[{"text":"Collagenous fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Phagocytes","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elastic fibers","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Glands","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Smooth muscle fibers","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21944,"text":"Which of the following correctly lists the protective coverings of the testes from outermost to innermost?","explanation":"The **parietal layer of tunica vaginalis** is the outermost layer, which is a serous membrane that partially covers the testis. It consists of two layers, one of which lines the scrotal cavity, while the other reflects back to form the visceral layer.\r\n\r\nThe **visceral layer of tunica vaginalis** is the next layer and closely adheres to the surface of the testis.\r\n\r\nThe **tunica albuginea** is a dense, fibrous capsule beneath the tunica vaginalis. It surrounds the testis and divides it into lobules.\r\n\r\nThe **tunica vasculosa**, also known as the tunica propria, is the innermost layer. It provides a network of blood vessels to nourish the testis and is located within the tunica albuginea.","reference":"Mescher AL. Junqueira’s Basic Histology: Text and Atlas. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Medical; 2018: 429.","responses":[{"text":"Parietal layer of tunica vaginalis, visceral layer of tunica vaginalis, tunica albuginea, tunica vasculosa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Tunica albuginea, tunica vasculosa, parietal layer of tunica vaginalis, visceral layer of tunica vaginalis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tunica vasculosa, parietal layer of tunica vaginalis, visceral layer of tunica vaginalis, tunica albuginea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Visceral layer of tunica vaginalis, parietal layer of tunica vaginalis, tunica albuginea, tunica vasculosa","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tunica vasculosa, tunica albuginea, parietal layer of tunica vaginalis, visceral layer of tunica vaginalis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21974,"text":"Which of the following ligaments anchors the ovary to the pelvic sidewall?","explanation":"The **suspensory ligament** of the ovary, also known as the infundibulopelvic ligament, is a double-layered fold of peritoneum that extends from the ovary to the lateral pelvic wall. This ligament contains important structures such as blood vessels, including the ovarian artery and vein, as well as nerves and lymphatics. The ovarian artery, a branch of the abdominal aorta, provides the main blood supply to the ovary, while the ovarian vein drains blood from the ovary.","reference":"Moore KL, Dalley AF, Agur AMR. Clinically Oriented Anatomy. 7th ed. Wolters Kluwer/Lippincott Williams \u0026 Wilkins Health; 2014: 399.","responses":[{"text":"Ovarian ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Interstitial ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Round ligament","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suspensory ligament","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Broad ligament","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21975,"text":"In which region of the male reproductive system are most sperms stored?","explanation":"The **epididymis** is a coiled, tube-like structure located on the posterior surface of the testes. It serves as a highly specialized site for the maturation, storage, and transport of sperm produced in the testes. During sperm production in the seminiferous tubules of the testes, the sperm are immature and incapable of motility. As they pass through the epididymis, they undergo a process of maturation and acquire the ability to swim (motility) and fertilize an egg (capacitation).\r\n\r\nThe epididymis provides a conducive environment for sperm maturation and serves as a reservoir where sperm can be stored for several weeks. When a male ejaculates, sperm are expelled from the epididymis into the vas deferens and subsequently into the urethra for ejaculation during sexual intercourse.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1014.","responses":[{"text":"Seminiferous tubules","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Epididymis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Prostate gland","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Seminal vesicles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vas deferens","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21976,"text":"During the menstrual cycle, if fertilization occurs, which hormone is primarily responsible for maintaining the corpus luteum and preventing its degeneration?","explanation":"After fertilization, when a sperm successfully fertilizes the egg and forms a zygote, the zygote begins to divide and develop into an embryo. This developing embryo produces **hCG,** which is a hormone specific to pregnancy. HCG has a similar structure to luteinizing hormone (LH), and it can bind to LH receptors on the corpus luteum.\r\n\r\nThe corpus luteum is a temporary endocrine structure that forms from the ruptured ovarian follicle after ovulation. It plays a crucial role in secreting progesterone, which is necessary to maintain the uterine lining (endometrium) and support early pregnancy.\r\n\r\nHCG, produced by the developing embryo, signals the corpus luteum to continue producing progesterone. This hormonal support is essential for the maintenance of pregnancy until the placenta takes over the production of hormones later in gestation.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1049.","responses":[{"text":"Estrogen","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gonadotropin releasing hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Human chorionic gonadotropin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicle stimulating hormone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Progesterone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21977,"text":"What is the role of the enzyme aromatase in the menstrual cycle?","explanation":"In the ovaries, during the early stages of the menstrual cycle, the developing ovarian follicles produce androgens, such as testosterone. **Aromatase acts on these androgens, converting them into estrogens, predominantly estradiol.** This conversion is important for the growth and maturation of the ovarian follicles and the preparation of the uterine lining (endometrium) for potential implantation in case of fertilization.\r\n\r\nAs the menstrual cycle progresses, the levels of estrogen rise and fall, influencing various aspects of the cycle, including the regulation of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH) secretion, which, in turn, drive ovulation and the formation of the corpus luteum.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1032.","responses":[{"text":"Initiating corpus luteum production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Converting androgens to estrogens","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitating ovulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Promoting FSH secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibiting progesterone production","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21978,"text":"Which hormone is responsible for the positive feedback loop leading to the surge in luteinizing hormone (LH) during ovulation?","explanation":"During the menstrual cycle, **estrogen** is produced primarily by the developing ovarian follicles in the ovaries. As the follicles mature, they release increasing amounts of estrogen into the bloodstream. When the estrogen levels reach a critical threshold, they trigger a positive feedback loop on the anterior pituitary gland. This positive feedback loop results in a rapid and dramatic increase in the secretion of LH.\r\n\r\nThe surge in LH is essential for the final maturation of the dominant follicle, its release from the ovary (ovulation), and the transformation of the remaining follicular cells into the corpus luteum, which secretes progesterone.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1040.","responses":[{"text":"Follicle stimulating hormone (FSH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Estrogen","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Progesterone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":21979,"text":"What is the primary function of the corpus luteum in the absence of pregnancy?","explanation":"The corpus luteum is a temporary endocrine structure that forms in the ovary after ovulation. Its formation is triggered when a mature follicle ruptures during ovulation, releasing the egg. The remaining structure, known as the corpus luteum, secretes hormones, primarily progesterone.\r\n\r\n**Progesterone plays a crucial role in preparing and maintaining the uterine lining** (endometrium) for possible implantation of a fertilized egg. It ensures that the endometrium remains thick, vascularized, and capable of supporting a potential pregnancy. This hormone also helps suppress uterine contractions, preventing premature shedding of the uterine lining and, consequently, menstruation.\r\n\r\nIf pregnancy does not occur, the corpus luteum eventually degenerates, leading to a decrease in progesterone production. This hormonal shift triggers the onset of menstruation and the shedding of the uterine lining, preparing the body for a new ovarian cycle.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1037.","responses":[{"text":"Inhibiting estrogen production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Initiating menstruation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Suppressing luteinizing hormone (LH) secretion","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Facilitating fertilization of the egg","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Producing progesterone to maintain the uterine lining","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":21980,"text":"In a laboratory, the hormone levels during different phases of the ovarian cycle of a 20-year-old female are monitored. During which of the following periods is the progesterone level the highest?","explanation":"The **progesterone level is the highest during the phase between ovulation and menstruation** in the ovarian cycle of a 20-year-old female.\r\n\r\nThis phase is known as the **luteal phase** and typically lasts for about 12-14 days in a typical 28-day ovarian cycle. The surge in progesterone production occurs due to the formation and function of the **corpus luteum**, which is a temporary endocrine structure that develops from the ruptured ovarian follicle after ovulation. The corpus luteum secretes progesterone, which prepares the uterine lining (endometrium) for possible implantation of a fertilized egg by making it more receptive and maintaining a suitable environment.\r\n\r\nDuring the proliferative phase, which occurs immediately after menstruation, estrogen levels are high, but progesterone remains relatively low. At the end of menstruation, hormone levels are generally low. Just before ovulation, there is a surge in luteinizing hormone (LH) and follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH), but progesterone levels are not yet elevated. During menstruation, both progesterone and estrogen levels are low as the previous cycle concludes.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1029, 1032.","responses":[{"text":"Immediately before ovulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"During menstruation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"During proliferative phase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"At the end of menstruation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Between ovulation and menstruation","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22103,"text":"What is the World Health Organization's (WHO) recommended age of initiation of weaning among normal-weight infants?","explanation":"At around **6 months,** most infants have reached a stage in their development where they are ready to start transitioning to solid foods alongside continued breastfeeding or formula feeding. This period is often referred to as the introduction of complementary foods. The introduction of complementary foods at this age is essential because it provides additional nutrients, vitamins, and minerals that are necessary for the growing infant.\r\n\r\nStarting weaning too early, such as at 3 months, may not be suitable for the infant's digestive system and could increase the risk of allergies and other health issues. Conversely, delaying weaning beyond 6 months may not provide adequate nutrition for the infant's growth and development.","reference":"(1) Infant and young child feeding. Accessed December 29, 2023. https://www.who.int/news-room/fact-sheets/detail/infant-and-young-child-feeding (2) Marcdante KJ, Kliegman RM, Schuh AM, Nelson WE, eds. Nelson Essentials of Pediatrics. 9th ed. Elsevier; 2023: 104.","responses":[{"text":"After 1 year","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"9 months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"3 months","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"6 months","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"1 year","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22105,"text":"Which one of the following is considered as the pillar of safe motherhood?","explanation":"**Antenatal care** refers to the medical care and support provided to pregnant women during their pregnancy. It plays a crucial role in ensuring the well-being of both the mother and the developing fetus. Regular antenatal check-ups help healthcare providers monitor the progress of the pregnancy, identify and address any potential complications or risks, and provide essential guidance on nutrition, hygiene, and lifestyle.\r\n\r\nAntenatal care ensures that pregnant women receive the necessary interventions and information to have a safe and healthy pregnancy, ultimately leading to the well-being of both the mother and the newborn.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Reproductive module-I; Subject: Community Medicine, Topic: Safe Motherhood.","responses":[{"text":"Adolescent health","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nutritional care","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mental health","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Women empowerment","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Antenatal care","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22107,"text":"A 35-year-old female, para 3+1, with a history of gestational diabetes during her previous pregnancy, wants to have prolonged contraception as she does not want to conceive. Which method of family planning would be appropriate for this patient?","explanation":"**IUCDs** are highly effective long-term contraceptive options that do not involve hormonal medications, making them suitable for women with a history of gestational diabetes. They are typically inserted into the uterus by a healthcare provider and can provide contraception for several years, depending on the type of IUCD chosen.\r\n\r\nWhile condoms and combined oral contraceptives are valid contraceptive options, they may not provide the desired long-term protection without regular user compliance. Injectable progestin contraceptives are hormonal and might not be the first choice for women with a history of gestational diabetes, as they can have hormonal effects.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 677.","responses":[{"text":"Intrauterine contraceptive devices (IUCD)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Vaginal rings","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Injectable progestin contraceptives","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Condoms","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Combined oral contraceptives","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22108,"text":"Which of the following methods of contraception inhibits ovulation?","explanation":"**Hormonal contraceptives,** such as birth control pills, patches, injections, and hormonal intrauterine devices (IUDs), contain synthetic hormones like estrogen and progestin. These hormones work by regulating the menstrual cycle and suppressing the release of eggs (ovulation) from the ovaries. By preventing ovulation, there is no egg available for fertilization by sperm, making it an effective method to prevent pregnancy.\r\n\r\nBarrier methods, such as condoms and diaphragms, physically block sperm from reaching the egg and do not affect ovulation.\r\n\r\nThe Copper T device is a type of intrauterine device (IUD) that contains copper and primarily works by creating an environment that is toxic to sperm, reducing their motility, but it does not inhibit ovulation.\r\n\r\nThe natural method relies on tracking a woman's menstrual cycle and avoiding intercourse during her fertile days but does not involve inhibiting ovulation.\r\n\r\nVasectomy is a permanent surgical procedure for men that involves cutting or blocking the vas deferens, preventing the release of sperm during ejaculation but has no impact on ovulation.","reference":"Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 41.","responses":[{"text":"Barrier methods","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Copper T device","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vasectomy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hormonal contraceptives","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Natural method","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22109,"text":"A 7-month pregnant lady visits an antenatal clinic for a regular checkup. Which vaccine must be recommended to this lady for safe delivery?","explanation":"**Tetanus** is a severe bacterial infection caused by *Clostridium tetani* and is often associated with contaminated wounds. In pregnant women, the risk of tetanus can increase during childbirth, particularly if proper hygiene practices are not followed. Tetanus can lead to muscle stiffness, spasms, and life-threatening complications for both the mother and the newborn.\r\n\r\nAdministering the Tetanus vaccine during pregnancy, specifically the Tetanus Toxoid vaccine, helps to protect both the mother and the baby by providing passive immunity. This vaccine stimulates the production of antibodies against tetanus, which can be transferred from the mother to the fetus, offering protection to the newborn during the vulnerable early months of life.","reference":"Vaccines during pregnancy FAQs | vaccine safety | CDC. Published August 11, 2022. Accessed December 30, 2023. https://www.cdc.gov/vaccinesafety/concerns/vaccines-during-pregnancy.html","responses":[{"text":"Typhoid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tuberculosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Rubella","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Measles","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tetanus","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22112,"text":"A 20-year-old unmarried girl presents to the outpatient department with complaints of scanty menstrual flow and excessive facial hair growth. Her menstrual cycles are irregular and she bleeds every 2 to 3 months. Clinically, she is obese with a body mass index (BMI) of 30 kg/m². Thyroid is not palpable. Her lab tests show an altered FSH/LH ratio, normal TSH, and prolactin. Pelvic ultrasound shows peripherally arranged follicles with increased ovarian volume. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**PCOS** is a common endocrine disorder that affects reproductive-aged women. It is characterized by multiple features, including anovulation (irregular menstrual cycles), hyperandrogenism (excessive facial hair growth), obesity, and polycystic ovaries on ultrasound. The altered FSH/LH ratio, indicative of an increased LH secretion relative to FSH, is a key hormonal imbalance seen in PCOS.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1022.","responses":[{"text":"Prolactinoma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Thyroid nodule","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Turner's syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22121,"text":"A 13-year-old female patient is brought by her mother to the gynecology outpatient department with complaints of monthly lower abdominal pain for one year. She has not started menstruating but her secondary characteristics are normal. On examination, a bluish tense bulge is seen at the introitus. Which structural anomaly of the pelvis is suspected in this patient?","explanation":"This condition is also known as congenital outflow tract obstruction of the uterus or vagina.\r\n\r\n**Mullerian obstruction** typically results from a developmental failure where the cervix and/or vagina fail to canalize properly. In this case, the patient likely has a form of obstructive Müllerian anomaly, such as an imperforate hymen or a transverse vaginal septum. These obstructions lead to the accumulation of menstrual blood in the uterus and/or vagina, which can manifest as cyclical pain corresponding with the menstrual cycle, despite the absence of visible menstrual flow. The bluish bulge at the introitus in this patient suggests the presence of a hematocolpos, where blood accumulates in the vagina.\r\n\r\n\r\nRenal anomalies may be associated with Müllerian anomalies but are not directly related to the symptoms described.\r\nMüllerian agenesis (e.g., Mayer-Rokitansky-Küster-Hauser syndrome) typically presents with primary amenorrhea but without cyclical pain and without a bulge at the introitus.\r\nMüllerian duplication usually involves anomalies like a double uterus or double vagina and does not typically present with obstruction.\r\nDiethylstilbestrol-related anomalies occur in offspring of women who took DES during pregnancy and involve a different spectrum of Müllerian anomalies.","reference":"Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 274.","responses":[{"text":"Mullerian obstruction","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Renal anomalies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Diethylstilbestrol related anomalies","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mullerian agenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mullerian duplication","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22129,"text":"A 28-year-old female, married for 5 years, para 3+0, all pre-term deliveries at 32, 30, and 30 weeks, is found to have a developmental anomaly on a hysterosalpingogram. What is the most common developmental anomaly of the uterus responsible for recurrent preterm deliveries in this patient?","explanation":"A **bicornuate uterus** is a type of congenital uterine malformation where the uterus has two \"horns\" due to incomplete fusion of the Mullerian ducts during fetal development. This condition is a part of the spectrum of uterine anomalies known as Müllerian duct anomalies.\r\n\r\nA bicornuate uterus is characterized by a deep indentation at the fundus, and it often presents with a heart-shaped appearance on imaging studies. Women with a bicornuate uterus are at increased risk for complications during pregnancy, including pre-term delivery, as seen in this patient. This is partly due to the abnormal shape of the uterus, which can interfere with the normal growth and positioning of the fetus, leading to issues like restricted fetal growth or abnormal presentation.\r\n\r\nA T-shaped uterus is often associated with exposure to diethylstilbestrol (DES) in utero and is less commonly associated with recurrent pre-term deliveries.\r\nComplete and partial septate uterus involve a septum dividing the uterine cavity, which can also lead to pregnancy complications, but they typically present more commonly with recurrent miscarriages rather than pre-term deliveries.\r\nAn aplastic uterus, or uterine agenesis, is a condition where the uterus is absent, which would not be consistent with the patient's history of multiple pregnancies.","reference":"(1) Sadler TW. Langman’s Medical Embryology. 14th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2018: 387.\r\n\r\n(2) Moore KL, Persaud TVN, Torchia MG. The Developing Human: Clinically Oriented Embryology. 11th ed. Saunders/Elsevier; 2020: 274.","responses":[{"text":"Complete septate uterus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Bicornuate uterus","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Partial septate uterus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"T-shaped uterus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aplastic uterus","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22130,"text":"Which of the following correctly identifies the reason why prostatic hyperplasia predominantly affects muscle fibers?","explanation":"The reason why prostatic hyperplasia predominantly affects **stromal cells** (muscle fibers) rather than epithelial cells is due to the localization and activity of **5 alpha-reductase** in the stromal cells.\r\n\r\nProstatic hyperplasia, also known as benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH), is characterized by the enlargement of the prostate gland. This condition primarily involves the proliferation of stromal cells and smooth muscle fibers within the prostate gland. The stromal cells play a crucial role in supporting the glandular tissue of the prostate.\r\n\r\nThe enzyme **5 alpha-reductase**, responsible for the conversion of testosterone to its more potent form, dihydrotestosterone (DHT), is mainly localized in the stromal cells of the prostate. DHT is a key factor in the development and growth of prostatic tissue. Its accumulation in the stromal cells leads to the proliferation of these cells, resulting in the enlargement of the prostate.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, Abul K Abbas, Jon C Aster, Ramzi S Cotran, and Stanley L Robbins. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier, 2020: 982.","responses":[{"text":"Epithelial cells do not proliferate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Overproduction of testosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"5 alpha-reductase is located only in stromal cells","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Dihydrotestosterone (DHT) is located only in the stromal cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Estrogenic effects","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22131,"text":"A 30-year-old male developed epididymitis. On culture, gram-negative diplococci, Neisseria gonorrhea, was located. Which one of the following laboratory culture media will be the most appropriate to grow this particular organism?","explanation":"*Neisseria gonorrhea* is a fastidious organism that requires special culture conditions for successful isolation. **Thayer-Martin agar** is a selective medium specifically designed to promote the growth of Neisseria species while inhibiting the growth of other bacteria that may be present in clinical specimens. This medium contains antibiotics and inhibitors that target competing flora, allowing Neisseria gonorrhea to thrive.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 124.","responses":[{"text":"Nutrient agar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blood agar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chocolate agar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Muller Hilton agar","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Thayer-Martin agar","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22133,"text":"Each year, there are an estimated 6 million new cases of syphilis globally in people aged 15-49 years. Which of the following best corresponds to the most common signs and symptoms of early or ''primary syphilis'' infection?","explanation":"The most common signs and symptoms of early or primary syphilis infection correspond to a **painless chancre** (a painless sore or ulcer) and **sores on the genitals and/or mouth**.\r\n\r\nSyphilis, caused by the bacterium *Treponema pallidum*, typically presents with a primary chancre at the site of infection, which is usually painless. This chancre can occur on the genitals, mouth, or other parts of the body where contact with the bacterium has taken place.","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, Abul K Abbas, Jon C Aster, Ramzi S Cotran, and Stanley L Robbins. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier, 2020: 372.","responses":[{"text":"Bullous pemphigoid infecting the limbs","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Painful chancre, sores on the face","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"High grade fever with body aches","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Painless chancre, sores on the genitals and/or mouth","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Green vaginal discharge","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22134,"text":"A healthy infant is born to a healthy mother; however, his weight decreases 5 to 10 percent within the first 2 to 3 days of his life. This may be due to which of the following reasons?","explanation":"**Loss of fluid from the body** is a normal and expected part of the neonatal transition. During pregnancy, the infant is surrounded by amniotic fluid, which is expelled from the lungs at birth. Additionally, the infant's kidneys become more efficient at filtering and excreting excess fluid. As a result, the newborn may pass urine and have bowel movements, leading to fluid loss.\r\n\r\nWhile the metabolism of brown fat for thermogenesis and the depletion of glycogen stores do occur in newborns to provide energy, they are not the primary reasons for the initial weight loss. The use of body proteins for energy is not a typical mechanism in healthy infants during the early postnatal period.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1066.","responses":[{"text":"Use of body proteins for energy","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Loss of fluid from the body","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Depletion of glycogen stores","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lungs get cleared of amniotic fluid","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Metabolism of brown fat for thermogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22142,"text":"A medical college student constantly feels overwhelmed and stressed about upcoming exams. She often thinks, ''I am going to fail; I am not good enough.'' What cognitive behavior therapy (CBT) technique would be most appropriate for her?","explanation":"**Cognitive restructuring** is a core component of CBT and is specifically designed to address and challenge irrational or negative thought patterns. In this technique, individuals learn to identify and reframe their distorted or unhelpful thoughts with more realistic and balanced ones. The goal is to replace self-defeating beliefs and cognitive distortions with healthier and more adaptive thinking patterns.\r\n\r\nIn the student's case, cognitive restructuring would help her recognize that her self-doubt and catastrophic thinking are not based on objective evidence. She would learn to challenge these negative thoughts and replace them with more positive and constructive beliefs about her abilities and exam performance. This process can significantly reduce anxiety and improve her overall mental well-being, allowing her to approach exams with greater confidence.","reference":"Cognitive restructuring: Steps, technique, and examples. Published June 20, 2022. Accessed December 29, 2023. https://www.medicalnewstoday.com/articles/cognitive-restructuring","responses":[{"text":"Behavior activation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cognitive restructuring","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Progressive muscle relaxation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Free association","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aversive conditioning","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22143,"text":"Mr. Xavier experiences a fear of public speaking, leading to avoidance of class presentations. Which cognitive behavior therapy (CBT) intervention would be most effective in addressing his fear?","explanation":"**Exposure therapy** is a widely used and evidence-based CBT approach for treating specific phobias, including the fear of public speaking. This technique involves gradually exposing the individual to the feared situation or stimulus, in this case, public speaking, in a controlled and systematic manner. The goal is to reduce anxiety and desensitize the person to the fear-inducing situation over time.\r\n\r\nIn Mr. Xavier's case, exposure therapy would involve progressively and repeatedly exposing him to speaking in front of others, starting with less anxiety-provoking situations and gradually moving towards more challenging ones. This approach helps individuals build confidence, confront their fears, and develop effective coping strategies.","reference":"What is exposure therapy? https://www.apa.org. Accessed December 29, 2023. https://www.apa.org/ptsd-guideline/patients-and-families/exposure-therapy","responses":[{"text":"Exposure therapy","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Progressive muscle relaxation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Aversive conditioning","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Behavior activation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cognitive rehearsal","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22155,"text":"A 28-year-old sexually active woman comes to the clinic with a complaint of yellowish-greenish, foul-smelling vaginal discharge. She experiences pain during sexual intercourse and has red spots on her vaginal walls. She also mentions having discomfort and a burning sensation while urinating. What is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Trichomoniasis** is a sexually transmitted infection (STI) caused by the protozoan parasite *Trichomonas vaginalis*. It is characterized by the mentioned symptoms, including the distinctive frothy, malodorous discharge. The presence of red spots on the vaginal walls is consistent with the inflammation and irritation caused by the parasite.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 988.","responses":[{"text":"Gonorrhea","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Donovanosis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Trichomoniasis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Chlamydial infection","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Syphilis","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22156,"text":"Based on the data gathered by the World Health Organization (WHO), which sexually transmitted virus is recognized as a significant cause of cervical cancer, infecting thousands of individuals annually?","explanation":"**HPV** is a group of viruses known to infect the genital and oral areas of both males and females. Certain high-risk strains of HPV, particularly types 16 and 18, are strongly associated with the development of cervical cancer. HPV infects cervical cells, leading to persistent infection and potentially causing changes in the cervical tissue that can progress to cancer over time.\r\n\r\nCervical cancer is a major global health concern, and vaccination against HPV has become a critical preventive measure to reduce the risk of cervical cancer in both males and females. Screening for HPV and early detection through regular Pap smears are essential components of cervical cancer prevention programs.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 149.","responses":[{"text":"Chlamydia trachomatis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hepatitis B virus","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"HIV","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Human papilloma virus (HPV)","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Herpes simplex type 2","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22157,"text":"Which of the following is related to the term ''chocolate cyst''?","explanation":"An **endometriotic cyst**, also known as an endometrioma, is a type of ovarian cyst that forms when endometrial tissue (the tissue that usually lines the uterus) implants and grows within the ovaries. Over time, these cysts can fill with dark, old blood, giving them a characteristic appearance resembling chocolate. The presence of endometrial tissue outside the uterus can lead to symptoms such as pelvic pain, painful menstruation, and infertility.\r\n\r\nSurface epithelial inclusion cysts are related to the lining of the ovaries, corpus luteal cysts involve the remnants of the ovarian follicle after ovulation, tubo-ovarian abscesses result from infections, and follicular cysts are associated with the development of ovarian follicles.","reference":"Sattar HA. Fundamentals of Pathology: Medical Course and Step 1 Review. Pathoma.com; 2021: 142.","responses":[{"text":"Corpus luteal cyst","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Tubo-ovarian abscesses","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicular cyst","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Endometriotic cyst","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Surface epithelial inclusion cyst","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22161,"text":"Young athletes who abuse androgens should be made aware of the side effects of these drugs. Which one of the following is, however, not of concern?","explanation":"Androgens, such as anabolic steroids, can have various adverse effects on the body. These effects may include stunted growth, overly aggressive behavior, decreased spermatogenesis (leading to infertility), and increased muscle mass (which is often a desired effect by athletes seeking performance enhancement).\r\n\r\nHowever, **anemia due to bone marrow failure** is not a common side effect associated with androgen abuse. Anemia is more often linked to other factors like nutritional deficiencies or other medical conditions, rather than direct bone marrow failure caused by androgens.","reference":"(1) Katzung BG, Todd W. Vanderah. Basic and Clinical Pharmacology. 15th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2021: 743. \r\n\r\n(2) Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 655.","responses":[{"text":"Increased muscle mass","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anemia due to bone marrow failure","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased spermatogenesis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Overly aggressive behavior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Stunted growth","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22162,"text":"A teenager seeks post-coital contraception. Which of the following preparations will be effective for this purpose?","explanation":"**Norgestrel,** a synthetic progestin, is commonly used in emergency contraception, often referred to as the \"morning-after pill.\" It is effective when taken shortly after unprotected intercourse, within a specific time frame, to prevent unintended pregnancy. Norgestrel functions by inhibiting or delaying ovulation, interfering with fertilization, and altering the uterine lining to reduce the likelihood of implantation if fertilization does occur.\r\n\r\nDiethylstilbestrol and Ethinyl estradiol are estrogen derivatives, Mifepristone is a medication used for medical abortion, and Clomiphene is used to induce ovulation in infertility treatment.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1043.","responses":[{"text":"Ethinyl estradiol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Norgestrel","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Diethylstilbestrol","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Clomiphene","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mifepristone","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22165,"text":"The process of PCR involves the amplification of DNA at high temperatures without the need to add fresh enzymes at each cycle. Which of the following enzymes is used in this process?","explanation":"**Taq polymerase,** derived from the thermophilic bacterium *Thermus aquaticus*, is exceptionally heat-stable. This property allows it to withstand the high temperatures required for DNA denaturation during PCR, typically around 94-98°C. Taq polymerase plays a pivotal role in replicating DNA by extending the primers and synthesizing complementary DNA strands during each PCR cycle.\r\n\r\nThe ability of Taq polymerase to function at elevated temperatures without denaturation makes it an indispensable enzyme in PCR. It enables the denaturation, annealing, and extension steps of the amplification process, facilitating the exponential amplification of the target DNA sequences.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 498. (2) Chatterjea MN, Shinde R. Textbook of Medical Biochemistry. 8th ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publications; 2012: 287.","responses":[{"text":"Ligase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Taq polymerase","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"RNA polymerase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Vent polymerase","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primase","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22166,"text":"The estrogen levels are found to be very high just after the end of menstruation. What is the main function of estrogen at this time?","explanation":"Estrogen is a crucial female sex hormone produced primarily by the developing ovarian follicles. During the menstrual cycle, estrogen levels rise significantly just after menstruation ends, during the follicular phase. One of its primary functions during this time is to stimulate the **proliferation and growth of the endometrial lining** of the uterus. This thickening of the endometrium prepares the uterus for possible implantation of a fertilized egg and provides a nurturing environment for early pregnancy.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1036.","responses":[{"text":"Endometrium proliferation","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Osteoclast production","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Maturation of stromal cells of ovaries","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior pituitary gland stimulation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Development of follicles","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22167,"text":"Blotting techniques are used to identify various protein and nucleic acid sequences. What is the correct sequence of steps in any blotting technique?","explanation":"Firstly, **electrophoresis** is performed to separate the molecules of interest based on their size or charge. In the case of DNA or RNA, this would mean separating fragments by size, while for proteins, it would be based on their charge and size.\r\n\r\nAfter electrophoresis, the molecules are typically transferred or **\"blotted\"** onto a membrane, such as nitrocellulose or nylon, creating a replica of the separated molecules on the membrane.\r\n\r\nFinally, **hybridization** is carried out, where a labeled probe (either DNA, RNA, or antibody, depending on the type of blotting) is used to detect and bind to specific target molecules on the membrane. This step allows for the identification of the specific sequences or proteins of interest.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 496. (2) Chatterjea MN, Shinde R. Textbook of Medical Biochemistry. 8th ed. Jaypee Brothers Medical Publications; 2012: 283.","responses":[{"text":"Blotting, hybridization, electrophoresis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Blotting, electrophoresis, hybridization","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Electrophoresis, blotting, hybridization","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Hybridization, blotting, electrophoresis","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Electrophoresis, hybridization, blotting","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22168,"text":"A 33-year-old male develops urethritis having a characteristic fishy smell. On culture, the pathogen isolated is found to be Ureaplasma urealyticum. The characteristic fishy smell on this condition is due to the production of which of the following substances?","explanation":"Ureaplasma urealyticum is a bacterium known for its ability to metabolize urea, which results in the production of **ammonia** as a metabolic byproduct. The release of ammonia into the genitourinary tract can lead to an alkaline environment, causing the characteristic fishy odor. This odor is particularly noticeable in conditions like bacterial vaginosis and urethritis.","reference":"Wolrath H, Borén H, Hallén A, Forsum U. Trimethylamine content in vaginal secretion and its relation to bacterial vaginosis. APMIS. Published November 2002. Accessed December 31, 2023. https://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1034/j.1600-0463.2002.1101108.x","responses":[{"text":"Carbon dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hydrogen sulfide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Carbon monoxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Nitrogen dioxide","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ammonia","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22169,"text":"A 35-year-old female with 32 weeks of gestational amenorrhea presents to the gynecology ward. Her ultrasound findings are placenta in the lower uterine segment covering the cervical os completely. What is the diagnosis?","explanation":"**Placenta previa** is a condition where the placenta abnormally implants in the lower uterine segment, partially or completely covering the cervical os. This can lead to bleeding during pregnancy, especially in the third trimester, and may necessitate a cesarean section (C-section) for a safe delivery. The condition is often associated with painless vaginal bleeding.\r\n\r\nIt's crucial to differentiate Placenta previa from other conditions involving abnormal placental attachment, such as Placenta accreta, increta, or percreta, which typically present with bleeding and adherence of the placenta to the uterine wall but do not involve the covering of the cervical os.","reference":"Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC, Cotran RS, Robbins SL. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1037.","responses":[{"text":"Abruptio placentae","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Placenta previa","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Placenta accreta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Placenta percreta","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Placenta increta","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22182,"text":"In the DNA hybridization technique, a single-stranded DNA probe is allowed to interact with a complementary sequence in a sample. What is this specific type of hybridization known as?","explanation":"**Southern blotting** is a molecular biology technique used to detect specific DNA sequences within a complex mixture of DNA. In this method, DNA samples are first fragmented by restriction enzymes and then separated by size through gel electrophoresis. Following electrophoresis, the DNA fragments are transferred (blotted) onto a membrane, typically a nitrocellulose or nylon membrane. A single-stranded DNA probe, labeled with a radioactive or non-radioactive marker, is used to hybridize specifically with the target DNA sequence of interest on the membrane.\r\n\r\nThis technique is particularly valuable for DNA fingerprinting, gene mapping, and identifying specific DNA sequences in genetic research.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 51.","responses":[{"text":"Western blotting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Southern blotting","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Northern blotting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Southwestern hybridization","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Fluorescence in situ hybridization","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22183,"text":"A 28-year-old man presents to the clinic with small, painless nodules in the genital region that have burst open creating beefy, red ulcers. The physician suspects it to be a case of Donovanosis. Which one of the following staining techniques will be used to diagnose the condition?","explanation":"Donovanosis, caused by the bacterium *Klebsiella granulomatis*, presents as small, painless nodules in the genital region, which later rupture to form characteristic beefy, red ulcers. Diagnosis of Donovanosis relies on identifying Donovan bodies, which are encapsulated organisms within macrophages, under microscopy. To do this, a biopsy of the lesion is obtained and stained with **Giemsa stain.** Giemsa staining helps visualize the intracellular Donovan bodies, which are distinctive for this condition.\r\n\r\nOther staining techniques like Ziehl-Neelsen, Gram, India ink, and Wright Giemsa are used for different purposes, such as diagnosing tuberculosis (Ziehl-Neelsen), identifying bacterial morphology (Gram), assessing cryptococcal infections (India ink), or staining blood cells (Wright Giemsa).","reference":"Kumar, Vinay, Abul K Abbas, Jon C Aster, Ramzi S Cotran, and Stanley L Robbins. Robbins \u0026 Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Elsevier, 2020: 371.","responses":[{"text":"Wright Giemsa stain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gram stain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ziehl neelsen stain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"India ink stain","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Giemsa stain","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22184,"text":"What is the blotting technique used when RNA is the target molecule for hybridization and the detection involves the use of a labeled probe?","explanation":"**Northern blotting** is a molecular biology technique used to study and analyze RNA molecules, including mRNA, rRNA, and tRNA. In this method, RNA samples are separated based on size through gel electrophoresis and then transferred (blotted) onto a membrane. After the transfer, a labeled probe, typically a complementary DNA or RNA sequence, is used to hybridize specifically with the target RNA molecules of interest. The labeled probe allows for the detection and visualization of the RNA molecules by autoradiography or other detection methods.\r\n\r\nIt's important to distinguish Northern blotting from other blotting techniques like Western (protein), Southern (DNA), and Southwestern (protein-DNA interaction) blotting, as each is designed for different types of molecules and purposes.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 51.","responses":[{"text":"Fluorescence in situ hybridization","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Southern blotting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Southwestern blotting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Western blotting","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Northern blotting","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22185,"text":"The initiation codon AUG that starts the translation process codes for which of the following amino acids?","explanation":"In the genetic code, AUG serves a dual role: it acts as both the initiation codon and codes for the amino acid **methionine.** When translation begins, the initiator tRNA carrying methionine (**Met-tRNAi**) recognizes the AUG start codon on the mRNA. Methionine is typically the first amino acid incorporated into the growing polypeptide chain during protein synthesis.\r\n\r\nMethionine is considered the \"start\" amino acid because it initiates the assembly of the protein chain, and it plays a pivotal role in the formation of the initial peptide bond between the first and second amino acids. Once this critical step occurs, the ribosome proceeds with the elongation phase of translation, adding additional amino acids to the growing polypeptide chain.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 445. (2) Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 42.","responses":[{"text":"Aspartate","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Cysteine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Methionine","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Glycine","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Alanine","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22187,"text":"Which of the following is the function of eIF-2-GTP during the eukaryotic translation process?","explanation":"During translation initiation, eIF-2 in its GTP-bound form binds to the initiator tRNA, which is charged with methionine (in eukaryotes, this is typically a methionine, as opposed to a formyl-methionine in prokaryotes). This complex then associates with the 40S ribosomal subunit. The eIF-2-GTP/initiator tRNA/40S ribosome complex scans the mRNA to find the start codon (AUG). Upon recognition of the start codon, GTP is hydrolyzed to GDP, and eIF-2-GDP is released. This release allows the 60S ribosomal subunit to join and form the complete 80S ribosome, positioning the initiator tRNA in the P site, ready for the elongation phase of protein synthesis.","reference":"Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 455.","responses":[{"text":"Prevent ribosomal reassociation","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"To transport initiating amino acyl tRNA to P site","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Guanine nucleotide exchange","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Translocaton","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Recognize stop codons","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22188,"text":"During translation, the ''non-traditional base pairing'' between the first nucleotide of the anticodon with the last nucleotide of the codon is most likely explained by which of the following?","explanation":"The **Wobble hypothesis** suggests that the rules of base pairing between the third nucleotide of a codon and the first nucleotide of the anticodon are somewhat relaxed, allowing for more flexibility in matching. Specifically, it allows for non-canonical base pairing, such as **G-U (guanine-uracil) pairing**, which is not typically seen in standard Watson-Crick base pairing. This flexibility is crucial for the versatility of the genetic code, as it means that a single tRNA molecule can recognize multiple codons with slight variations.","reference":"(1) Ferrier DR. Lippincott’s Illustrated Reviews: Biochemistry. 8th ed. Wolters Kluwer; 2020: 453. (2) Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 35.","responses":[{"text":"Shine-Dalgarno sequence","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Wobble hypothesis","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Central dogma","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Charging of tRNA","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ubiquitination","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22191,"text":"While discussing a model of the pelvis, a student points out the levator ani muscle as one of the boundaries of the ischiorectal fossa. Which of the following correctly identifies the location of the levator ani muscle in relation to this fossa?","explanation":"In relation to the **ischiorectal fossa**, the **levator ani muscle** is **medial**. \r\n\r\nThe ischiorectal fossa is a diamond-shaped space located on each side of the rectum. It is bounded laterally by the **ischial tuberosity and the sacrotuberous ligament**, posteriorly by the **gluteus maximus muscle**, and anteriorly by the **levator ani muscle**. \r\n\r\nThe levator ani muscle is a critical component of the pelvic floor musculature, and it plays a crucial role in supporting the pelvic viscera and maintaining continence. Its medial location forms the anterior boundary of the ischiorectal fossa and contributes to the structural integrity of the pelvic region.","reference":"Drake RL. Gray’s Anatomy for Students. 4th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 498.","responses":[{"text":"Posterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Lateral","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Medial","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Anterior","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Base","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22192,"text":"Which of the following does not play any part in the formation of the gonadal ridge during the development of the reproductive system?","explanation":"The development of the gonadal ridge, which is the precursor to the gonads (ovaries or testes), primarily involves contributions from the mesothelium, primordial germ cells, coelomic epithelium, and local mesenchyme (embryonic connective tissue).\r\n\r\nThe mesothelium, a layer of cells derived from the mesoderm, and the underlying coelomic epithelium proliferate and penetrate the underlying mesenchyme to form the gonadal ridge.\r\nPrimordial germ cells, which originate from the yolk sac, migrate to the developing gonadal ridges and play a critical role in the formation of the germ cells (sperm or oocytes).\r\nThe local mesenchyme provides the structural and connective tissue support for the developing gonadal ridge.\r\n\r\n**Ectodermal cells**, in contrast, are involved in the formation of structures like the skin, nervous system, and certain sensory organs, but they do not contribute to the development of the gonadal ridge.","reference":"Dow lecture slides. Reproductive module-I; Subject: Embryology, Topic: Development of Male Reproductive System.","responses":[{"text":"Primordial germ cells","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Mesothelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Local mesenchyme (embryonic connective tissue)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Coelomic epithelium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Ectodermal cells","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22193,"text":"Which of the following provides an important negative feedback mechanism for the control of spermatogenesis?","explanation":"**Inhibin** is a hormone produced by the Sertoli cells within the seminiferous tubules of the testes. Its primary role is to regulate the production of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) by the anterior pituitary gland.\r\n\r\nWhen there is an excess of inhibin produced, typically in response to a sufficient number of sperm being present in the seminiferous tubules, inhibin inhibits the secretion of FSH. FSH is a hormone that plays a critical role in stimulating the growth and maturation of sperm cells within the testes.\r\n\r\nBy inhibiting FSH secretion, inhibin helps to prevent excessive spermatogenesis and maintains the proper balance of sperm production.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1032.","responses":[{"text":"Testosterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Inhibin","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Luteinizing hormone (LH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Gonadotropin releasing hormone (GnRH)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Follicle stimulating hormone (FSH)","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22194,"text":"During capacitation, the permeability of the sperm membrane to which of the following ions increases significantly, altering the flagellum's activity and transforming it from a previously gentle undulating motion to a vigorous whip-like motion?","explanation":"The sperm cell undergoes a series of changes during capacitation to prepare for fertilization. One of the key changes involves an increase in intracellular **calcium** levels. This increase in calcium ions within the sperm's cytoplasm is essential for altering the flagellar motion from a gentle undulating motion to a more vigorous whip-like motion.","reference":"Hall JE, Hall ME. Guyton and Hall Textbook of Medical Physiology. 14th ed. Elsevier; 2020: 1015.","responses":[{"text":"Sodium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Chloride","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Magnesium","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Calcium","correct":true,"visible":false},{"text":"Potassium","correct":false,"visible":false}]},{"id":22195,"text":"A 38-year-old woman is concerned about the potential decline in fertility as she approaches menopause. Which hormonal changes are characteristic of the perimenopause period?","explanation":"As a woman approaches menopause, her ovarian function begins to decline, leading to reduced estrogen production. In response to this decrease in estrogen, the hypothalamus-pituitary axis becomes more active, leading to **increased secretion of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH)**. Elevated FSH and LH levels are often used as diagnostic markers for perimenopause.\r\n\r\nDuring this transitional period, estrogen levels can fluctuate, leading to various symptoms like hot flashes and mood swings. Progesterone levels may also decrease, contributing to changes in the menstrual cycle.\r\n\r\nInhibin, on the other hand, typically decreases as a result of declining ovarian function.\r\n\r\nElevated prolactin levels are not a characteristic feature of perimenopause but may occur in other conditions such as hyperprolactinemia.","reference":"(1) Barrett KE, Brooks HL, Barman SM, Yuan JXJ. Ganong’s Review of Medical Physiology. 26th ed. McGraw-Hill Education; 2019: 397.\r\n\r\n(2) Costanzo L. Costanzo Physiology. 7th ed. Elsevier, Inc; 2021: 481.","responses":[{"text":"Increased estrogen and progesterone","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Reduced inhibin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Decreased estrogen only","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated prolactin","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Elevated FSH and LH","correct":true,"visible":false}]},{"id":22196,"text":"A 32-year-old male presents to the reproductive endocrinology clinic with a complaint of not having children since he got married. The patient reports a lack of facial and body hair development, reduced muscle mass, and diminished libido. Upon further investigation, his plasma testosterone levels are found to be significantly low with low levels of follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH) and luteinizing hormone (LH). Which of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","explanation":"**Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism** refers to a condition in which the gonads (testes in males) fail to produce adequate sex hormones due to a deficiency in gonadotropin-releasing hormone (GnRH), which is responsible for stimulating the release of FSH and LH from the pituitary gland. In this case, the low levels of FSH and LH suggest a dysfunction at the hypothalamic-pituitary level.\r\n\r\nThe presence of a genetic mutation can disrupt the normal regulation of GnRH secretion, leading to decreased FSH and LH levels and subsequently reduced testosterone production. This condition often results in symptoms such as delayed puberty, low libido, and infertility.","reference":"Le T, Bhushan V, Qiu C, et al., eds. First Aid for the USMLE Step 1 2023. 33rd ed. McGraw Hill; 2023: 658.","responses":[{"text":"Androgen insensitivity syndrome","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Primary testicular failure (hypergonadotropic hypogonadism)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Klinefelter syndrome (47, XXY)","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypothalamic-pituitary dysfunction","correct":false,"visible":false},{"text":"Hypogonadotropic hypogonadism due to a genetic mutation","correct":true,"visible":false}]}
]

